eriodically decriminalization and legalization movements arise. Debates continue over whether the problems of addiction and crime associated with illicit use of drugs stem from their illegal status or the nature of the drugs themselves. In The Long War on Drugs Anne L. Foster explores the origin of the punitive approach to drugs and its continued appeal despite its obvious flaws. She provides a comprehensive overview, focusing not only on a political history of policy developments but also on changes in medical practices and understanding of drugs. Foster also outlines the social and cultural changes prompting different attitudes about drugs; the racial, environmental, and social justice implications of particular drug policies; and the international consequences of US drug policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDrug abusexGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aDrug abusexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aDrug abusexPrevention. 0aDrug abusexSocial aspects. 0aDrug abusezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aDrug abusezUnited States. 0aDrug controlzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aDrug controlzUnited States. 0aDrug legalizationzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027553?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97814780275534